1
00:00:06,882 --> 00:00:11,053
I just love your writing, Tom,
ever since <i>Scorpio.</i>

2
00:00:11,136 --> 00:00:13,471
I think it just gets better and better.

3
00:00:13,556 --> 00:00:16,684
Oh, yeah?
What else have you read?

4
00:00:16,767 --> 00:00:21,396
All of them. I thought
the latest was brilliant, <i>God's Cauldron.</i>

5
00:00:21,479 --> 00:00:24,357
- You read that?
- In one sitting.

6
00:00:24,441 --> 00:00:28,070
But what we'd really love to read
is your book on the Underwoods.

7
00:00:28,153 --> 00:00:32,157
- Well, it's changed. It's fiction now.
- But based on them.

8
00:00:34,076 --> 00:00:35,703
People might draw parallels.

9
00:00:35,786 --> 00:00:37,830
Would the Underwoods find it flattering?

10
00:00:37,913 --> 00:00:39,790
I don't think they'd be too happy with it.

11
00:00:39,873 --> 00:00:42,000
How do you think it'll do?

12
00:00:43,251 --> 00:00:46,171
- Who knows?
- Better than <i>God's Cauldron,</i> I hope.

13
00:00:46,254 --> 00:00:49,007
Sales were disappointing, weren't they?

14
00:00:49,091 --> 00:00:50,342
In fact, they've been disappointing

15
00:00:50,425 --> 00:00:53,386
on everything you've written
the past ten years.

16
00:00:53,470 --> 00:00:56,306
We can change that with this new book.

17
00:00:56,389 --> 00:00:58,475
I'm not a political tool.

18
00:00:58,559 --> 00:01:00,894
We didn't fly you up here
because my wife's a fan.

19
00:01:00,978 --> 00:01:03,021
I'm sure you had a notion
of what we're after.

20
00:01:03,105 --> 00:01:04,982
I didn't have any expectations.

21
00:01:05,899 --> 00:01:07,525
I just came because I was curious.

22
00:01:07,610 --> 00:01:11,113
Well, then let me satisfy your curiosity.

23
00:01:11,196 --> 00:01:13,323
If your book can hurt the Underwoods,

24
00:01:13,907 --> 00:01:16,076
we want it to be published
before the election,

25
00:01:16,159 --> 00:01:18,411
and we want it to be big.

26
00:01:18,495 --> 00:01:20,831
Dana Treister, do you know her?

27
00:01:20,914 --> 00:01:22,332
The editor of <i>Vanity Fair.</i>

28
00:01:22,415 --> 00:01:26,712
- That's right. She's a close friend.
- And Ben Grant, founder of Pollyhop.

29
00:01:26,795 --> 00:01:27,963
I saw the webcast.

30
00:01:28,046 --> 00:01:30,048
They don't manipulate
search results,

31
00:01:30,132 --> 00:01:33,343
but let's just say
a big spread in <i>Vanity Fair...</i>

32
00:01:33,426 --> 00:01:34,970
Nice juicy excerpt,

33
00:01:35,053 --> 00:01:39,182
profile on Thomas Yates,
his literary comeback.

34
00:01:39,266 --> 00:01:43,395
We're on the cover this month, but...
next month it could be you.

35
00:01:43,478 --> 00:01:47,065
I'm on the Marxist side of Democrat.

36
00:01:47,149 --> 00:01:51,236
- Why would I help a Republican?
- You'd be helping yourself, Tom.

37
00:01:51,319 --> 00:01:53,321
And if that helps us
a little bit along the way,

38
00:01:53,405 --> 00:01:55,365
what's the harm in that?

39
